(1115, '<div style="text-align: justify;">Ive just finished a feature for a trade magazine regarding wine preservation systems such as Enomatic and By the Glass cabinets and how they are increasingly expanding in the on-trade on the back of a demand from consumers for better quality wines in smaller measures. Frederic Robinson which owns a 352-wide on-trade estate across the north west has installed two By the Glass preservation and serving units in its gastropubs: The Red Lion in Stockport and The Spinner and Bergamot in Cheshire, with 10 to be in-house by the end of the year. One of the reasons to introduce a more expensive offering at its destination sites is that consumers do a lot of driving to venues these days, so if they can only drink one glass - they''d like it to good. For wine lovers it can be a crushing disappointment when youre faced with a decent food menu, but lousy drinks one.</div>\r\n<div style="text-align: justify;"></div>\r\n<div style="text-align: justify;"></div>\r\n<div style="text-align: justify;">Last Friday, I was allocated driver for the evening and drove to a reputable independent restaurant and deli, which is also a wine and spirits retailer. I was really looking forward to one quality glass of something with my food. But I was astounded to see on the menu just two whites and two reds. Not only that; the two whites were an entry level Sauvignon Blanc and Pinot Grigio. My heart sank. I felt like Id been thrown back into the dark ages when a glass of semi-oxidised house Chardonnay or Cabernet Sauvignon were the only options. I spoke to London''s Fulham Wine rooms the other day which has an impressive alternating choice of 48 wines by the glass on its list. Fair enough, it may be aided by Enomatic machines that help preserve the wines for up to a month and that cost a fair bit of dosh to buy in.But Im not looking for 48 wines necessarily - just more than two - and with bit of imagination thrown in.<br /> <br /> <br /> With all the wine preservation aids around now, there''s no excuse. Businesses such as this are overlooking great opportunities to add to their reputation and maximise profits. According to Frederic Robinsons'' wine and spirits buyer, Noel Reid, the results from its wines-by-the-glass push has "exceeded all expectations". There''s a massive opportunity here for it to be a win-win situation for both consumers and businesses alike. Particularly in the north west, where in many restaurants decent wine-by-the-glass offerings just do not seem to have caught on and caught up. I''ll stop complaining soon, honest.</div>'),
