(640, '<p></p>\r\n<p class="MsoNormal">It amazes me that many restaurant and food businesses can carry on for years, turnover millions, hire dozens of chefs and never step back and review the real issues of how they can either make more money or reduce the potential losses in their kitchens. A single restaurant for example, can usually invest over 100,000 in a new kitchen and new staff team and launch with their fingers crossed, without even considering a solid food profit strategy or introducing a bit of science by creating secure and well documented systems and procedures that will help guarantee the food side of the business is efficient and waste resistant as possible. Experienced operators call this de-risking, because they know that the food production line from ordering from suppliers to delivering hot and delicious meals to delighted customers is fraught with opportunities for leakage and heartache.</p>\r\n<p class="MsoNormal">I remember being sat around a boardroom table once, with the MD of a group of hotels and restaurants barking and banging on at his general managers about how their respective businesses were consistently falling behind with their profitability targets and food gross margins. When I plucked up the courage, cleared my throat and suggested that instead, Wouldnt it be better to gather the group Head Chefs and put their heads together and create a company kitchen and food procedures manual? I could have been speaking in Mongolian for the reaction I received. I knew the company was in a straightjacket, using age old motivation techniques such as threats, pressure and big sticks. Believe me, common sense and procedures are rarely implemented from top down, especially when there are daily, weekly and monthly pressures of running a business to contend with.</p>\r\n<p class="MsoNormal">So, what can be achieved by stepping back and reviewing a large companys overall and combined kitchen procedures, or even those of a single site operation? After all, how many business owners have had to take a deep breath as yet another of their chefs decries important procedures, systems and pricing policies, referring to them as irrelevant to their own small, quality, fresh, kitchens like ours? Its fair to say that nearly every kitchen in the country is off target and inefficient when looked at closely. After all, a restaurant or food business is rarely a simple process and can be one of the hardest business models to get right. For a start, food is expensive, delicate and perishable with a limited shelf life. Then it has to be handled with care, great skill and expertise so as to ensure that as much as possible of the produce ordered, received, stored, prepared, cooked, served and paid for isnt wasted or unaccounted for in one of over a hundred places somewhere along the line. No wonder so many hospitality business operators prefer the safer life instead, dealing in beds, bottles and barrels with fewer opportunities for error.</p>\r\n<p class="MsoNormal">With all the best procedures and systems in the world, compared to other business types, restaurants and food businesses still have to contend with even more unpalatable variables. Unlike most professional office based businesses, who have the luxury of dealing with their clients on the phone, by email, or scheduled appointments in regular office hours and air conditioned meeting rooms, customer flows of even the most established restaurants and food businesses are rarely predictable, usually not even booked, often alcohol fuelled and always demanding consistency and value. Theres no business like it. And yet, in catering, even more is usually left to luck, judgement and experience. Battles and wars have been lost by brave, battle hardened but poorly prepared generals and soldiers and by the same token experienced, skilled but less than perfectly organised restaurateurs and their chefs have had unexpectedly poor months and bailiffs at the door. Whether youre starting a food business for the first time or beginning to roll out a proven food concept, its no longer just about location, taste, presentation, recruitment, marketing and design after all.</p>\r\n<p class="MsoNormal">Like so many of you, Ive worked with good and bad food businesses since washing up and preparing pub lunches at the age of 14. The subjects of food, customers, profit, chefs and success have fascinated and frustrated me so much that Ive made them my life, committing to being scientific and structured in reviewing and proposing safe, sensible but profitable solutions for fellow business owners. Why? Because over the last few years Ive seen enough to convince me that truly successful, profitable, food led businesses are more than just a chance balance of art and science. Theyre rare and almost incredible  and I love them.</p>\r\n<p><img src="{CCM:FID_93}" alt="IMG_0139small.jpg" width="177" height="200" /></p>'),
(641, '<div class="testBlock">\r\n<div class="testBlockInner">\r\n<div class="testBlockInner">\r\n<p>We joined Hospitality Entrepreneur in November 2013 and the benefits of being members have been truly ''business changing'' already.</p>\r\n<p>Having a 24/7 expert resource and access to industry leading Partner businesses has transformed the way we operate, instantly improving gross profits, saving us loads of time each week and could ultimately increase the value of our business by as much as 200,000 within 12 months. Not bad for an initial investment of just 120. After 6 years in business, the future suddenly looks good!</p>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class="testbottom"></div>\r\n<img src="{CCM:BASE_URL}/files/6913/9454/8783/test-image.png" alt="" />\r\n<h5>Andrew and Claire Bowen<span> Java &amp; Co, Oxford and Abingdon</span></h5>\r\n</div>'),
