(214, '  \r\nWHY RESTAURANTS FAIL \r\nA hospitality business coachs review and reflections after BBC2s The Restaurant Man, aired on Wednesday 26th February. \r\nIt doesnt matter whether its a huge name like Keith Floyd or a previously unknown like Nahida of Coventry, the world is littered with buildings where restaurant owners have failed. In last nights episode of BBC2sThe Restaurant Man, I watched Russell Norman as he observed and attempted to mentor successful mother of many and home cook Nahida in her efforts to open and run Desi Fusion, her restaurant dream in Coventry.Rregular viewers of the programme or first time watchers could hardly have expected the restaurant to have been an overnight success. The near future will tell for certain, but all the signs are that Nahidas dream and the savings of her family and friends will disappear down the less than adequate Desi Fusions plumbing. \r\nEarly in the programme Norman reminds us that restaurants are many times more likely to fail than almost any other business, even before they open. Exact statistics are hard to find, but at least 2,000 restaurants and just as many pubs closed last year alone. So, why is the mortality rate so high? Instead of blaming global and national factors such as the economy, government legislation, weather or even plain old bad luck, at long last and with the benefit of hindsight some of the casualties will now admit that they would have done things differently or shouldnt have opened their business in the first place. Despite this statistic and relentless trend, thousands of restaurants and other hospitality businesses will continue to open in 2014. Unfortunately very few will have a business plan and even fewer, especially the small and independent ones, will make any money at all. \r\nSo, why do restaurants fail? For the same reasons as any small or medium sized business. OK, so academics and theoreticians will drool over economic laws that must not be broken. Marketing gurus will always cite lack of sales and marketing activity. Food bloggers will say that a failed restaurants menu and cooking just wasnt good enough. Designers will point at inadequate or inappropriate colours, lighting, fabric and furniture. The reasons are in truth almost limitless. However, the one sad truth that is often even more unpalatable than the restaurants food is the total unsuitability of the restaurant owner to own and run their own establishment, or any business for that matter. Unfortunately family and friends will almost always be supportive or encouraging to would-be restaurant owners, perhaps even offering healthy and friendly criticism about wall colours, table cloths, or proposed locations in the months or years that lead up to the purchase of the site that will soon breathe life into their dreams. Rarely though, will independent restaurant owners be asked by nearest and dearest if they have the essential character traits, business skills and acumen to start, run and make a success of their own business. Nahidas naivety was no doubt excruciatingly exaggerated for the watchability of television and not for the first time as viewing veterans of Kitchen Nightmares or The Hotel Inspector will now be aware. But sadly, I very much doubt if her ideas or business planning amounted to anything more than unrealistic discussions over the hearty family dinner table. Similarly, most failed or failing restaurant owners (and there are tens of thousands out there) spent less time ruthlessly planning their business than they did over deciding a new car, shopping at Christmas or picking a family holiday.  \r\nLooking in the mirror and asking, Am I really 100% prepared and totally serious about opening this restaurant? is one thing that beginners in hospitality have to do more often, but the same mirror is rarely qualified to give an answer. Bank managers on the other hand are definitely qualified. Or are they? Nahida, we are told, was given a 20,000 bank loan which didnt even get her across the starting line and, as Norman was quick to point out, didnt even cover her essential opening expenses. Across the land, owners of thriving restaurants find it difficult to borrow money sensibly or even secure an overdraft facility from the banks and must be envious or anguished at the thought that someone with no experience, no business plan and very little suitability for running their own business could have been granted any bank support at all. I can detect a public outcry and castigation of the bank manager or, more likely, computer that gave Nahida enough rope with which to go and hang herself (as the saying goes)and her dreams. In reality her chances of making a success, even watched and supported by an expert like Norman, were about as high as someone who likes having a bath at home and then going on to swim the Channel. \r\nAfter more than 20 years of advising and mentoring successful and not so successful hospitality business owners and having my own share of huge victories and a few calamities in running pubs and restaurants myself, I can with certainty blame most restaurant failures on the owners themselves and their lack of suitability, reluctance to take experienced advice and unwillingness to prepare a business plan before they even opened their doors for business. On the same day that I watched The Restaurant Man with a huge amount of sadness, I had three separate phone calls over nearly four hours discussing the detail and arranging the implementation of an online and offline marketing plan with a sensible business person set to open a rural pub in four months time. The contrast between Nahida and the client I spoke to yesterday in their suitability and chances of success dont even need to be told. I sincerely wish Nahida well. Shes a wonderful woman and has a lovely family and I hope I can meet her when she proves me wrong. However, whilst running the gauntlet of being on national television and by ignoring the advice of one of the best in the business I fear shes lost somewhere in excess of 50,000, a huge amount of time shell never get back, her job and has probably become very stressed an unwell in the process. On the other hand she may come out of the battle stronger, like a true entrepreneur, but only if she learns from the lessons and knocks shes received and implements some basic but essential actions immediately, unlike the thousands who didnt in the last year alone.  \r\n \r\nPeter Austen \r\nwww.hospitalityentrepreneur.com \r\n27.02.14  ', 'WHY RESTAURANTS FAIL', '', '/blog/2014/02/first-blog-post', '2014-02-24 14:31:00', '2014-09-01 13:38:24', NULL, 0),
(275, 'Nigel Botterill - Owner - Entrepreneur''s Circle - It''s time for a totally ''Done-For-You'' marketing service for the hospitality sector - "Having known and worked with Peter Austen for a couple of great years now, we decided it''s time for a totally ''Done-For-You'' marketing service for the hospitality sector. We''re really proud and excited to be part of HE, providing members with our world-class team of marketers driving a steady flow of new customers into your business."  The UKs Largest Membership Organisation Dedicated to Helping Business Grow\r\nKey services and benefits to members\r\n In the last 8 years Nigel Botterill has built 8 separate 1m businesses from scratch, so he knows a thing or two about business growth. Nigels Entrepreneurs Circle is the UKs largest membership organisation dedicated to helping business grow. With a national network of Business Growth Advisors (BGAs) and 130 local meetings each month across the UK, thousands of entrepreneurs have been helped by discovering new ideas and then making them work in their own businesses. Now we have joined forces to launch a business advice and ''done for you'' marketing service tailored for hospitality.  All Hospitality Entrepreneur (HE) ''Starter'' members gain marketing and business growth advice and tips from Nigel and his advisors from Day 1, posted regularly on our website and blogs. Whilst Starter subscription to HE does not include membership of the Entrepreneurs Circle, you can qualify for preferential and exclusive joining fees, especially for the new Club Plus membership level which we are launching in March. \r\nHow this can help you\r\n\r\nBusiness strategy\r\nHow to maximise you Marketing\r\nmuch much more\r\n\r\n See our Membership page to find out how you can join Nigels Entrepreneurs Circle and have automatic exclusive access to his Club Plus Membership (usually 299 per month) and an additional marketing and business growth package that has been tailored to our industry.  2009 - Marketing and Business Growth -  -  - Helping business owners ESCAPE MEDIOCRITY and living the life you want to lead...  Resources Supplied By Entrepreneur''s Circle ', 'Entrepreneurs Circle', '', '/partners/entrepren', '2014-03-04 16:06:00', '2014-09-01 13:38:24', NULL, 0);
