(264, ' The world seems to be going mad for quotations, especially those that motivate us, as most of our Facebook friends timeline posts will show us. Like quotations or not, theyre rarely invented and usually act as a great reminder of how super-successful people have achieved all sorts of goals in the past. Ali Carter brought this quote to my attention yesterday: \r\n What is the distance between someone who achieves their goals consistently and those who spend their lives and careers merely following? The extra mile (US business guru Gary Blair) \r\n OK, so I dont know Gary Blair. However, every staff appraisal Ive ever conducted and self appraisal form Ive ever issued asksthe staff member to consider whether or not they go the extra mile and how often? \r\n A few thoughts. Have you explained clearly what is expected of them and discussed each others definition of this elusive extra mile? Have you recognised them for going the extra bit and thanked them for it? You can bet they wont do it again if you dont, so why not go the extra mile yourself and really look for good actions and examples of your staff team members going the extra mile? Its One small step for man, but a huge potential step for hospitality business kind, or whatever Neil Armstrong said.  ', 'GOING THE EXTRA BIT', '', '/blog/2014/03/members-blog-post-1', '2014-03-03 16:42:00', '2014-09-01 13:38:26', NULL, 0),
(265, ' It amazes me that many restaurant and food businesses can carry on for years, turnover millions, hire dozens of chefs and never step back and review the real issues of how they can either make more money or reduce the potential losses in their kitchens. A single restaurant for example, can usually invest over 100,000 in a new kitchen and new staff team and launch with their fingers crossed, without even considering a solid food profit strategy or introducing a bit of science by creating secure and well documented systems and procedures that will help guarantee the food side of the business is efficient and waste resistant as possible. Experienced operators call this de-risking, because they know that the food production line from ordering from suppliers to delivering hot and delicious meals to delighted customers is fraught with opportunities for leakage and heartache. \r\nI remember being sat around a boardroom table once, with the MD of a group of hotels and restaurants barking and banging on at his general managers about how their respective businesses were consistently falling behind with their profitability targets and food gross margins. When I plucked up the courage, cleared my throat and suggested that instead, Wouldnt it be better to gather the group Head Chefs and put their heads together and create a company kitchen and food procedures manual? I could have been speaking in Mongolian for the reaction I received. I knew the company was in a straightjacket, using age old motivation techniques such as threats, pressure and big sticks. Believe me, common sense and procedures are rarely implemented from top down, especially when there are daily, weekly and monthly pressures of running a business to contend with. \r\nSo, what can be achieved by stepping back and reviewing a large companys overall and combined kitchen procedures, or even those of a single site operation? After all, how many business owners have had to take a deep breath as yet another of their chefs decries important procedures, systems and pricing policies, referring to them as irrelevant to their own small, quality, fresh, kitchens like ours? Its fair to say that nearly every kitchen in the country is off target and inefficient when looked at closely. After all, a restaurant or food business is rarely a simple process and can be one of the hardest business models to get right. For a start, food is expensive, delicate and perishable with a limited shelf life. Then it has to be handled with care, great skill and expertise so as to ensure that as much as possible of the produce ordered, received, stored, prepared, cooked, served and paid for isnt wasted or unaccounted for in one of over a hundred places somewhere along the line. No wonder so many hospitality business operators prefer the safer life instead, dealing in beds, bottles and barrels with fewer opportunities for error. \r\nWith all the best procedures and systems in the world, compared to other business types, restaurants and food businesses still have to contend with even more unpalatable variables. Unlike most professional office based businesses, who have the luxury of dealing with their clients on the phone, by email, or scheduled appointments in regular office hours and air conditioned meeting rooms, customer flows of even the most established restaurants and food businesses are rarely predictable, usually not even booked, often alcohol fuelled and always demanding consistency and value. Theres no business like it. And yet, in catering, even more is usually left to luck, judgement and experience. Battles and wars have been lost by brave, battle hardened but poorly prepared generals and soldiers and by the same token experienced, skilled but less than perfectly organised restaurateurs and their chefs have had unexpectedly poor months and bailiffs at the door. Whether youre starting a food business for the first time or beginning to roll out a proven food concept, its no longer just about location, taste, presentation, recruitment, marketing and design after all. \r\nLike so many of you, Ive worked with good and bad food businesses since washing up and preparing pub lunches at the age of 14. The subjects of food, customers, profit, chefs and success have fascinated and frustrated me so much that Ive made them my life, committing to being scientific and structured in reviewing and proposing safe, sensible but profitable solutions for fellow business owners. Why? Because over the last few years Ive seen enough to convince me that truly successful, profitable, food led businesses are more than just a chance balance of art and science. Theyre rare and almost incredible  and I love them. \r\n   ', 'FOOD PROFIT STRATEGY DO YOU BELIEVE IN LUCK OR SCIENCE?', '', '/blog/2014/03/members-2', '2014-03-03 16:43:00', '2014-09-01 13:38:26', NULL, 0),
