(310, 'The paradox of choice, by Carol Emmas  Lately there seems to be just too much choice in life and it''s tiring. For instance, only a few years ago we had five TV stations, now there are hundreds and it takes forever to pick a channel if youre just lazily scrolling through via remote control. Then take social media; if you want to keep up with goings on there is Twitter, Facebook, Pintrest and blogs galore. We could lose days of our lives on Twitter alone choosing what links we want to click on to. If you totted up all the minutes spent making across-the-board choices, I reckon wed lose months of our lives.\r\n\r\nWine choice is the same. Sometimes when youre staring at the shelves the bottles just swim into one. I walked out of M&S today empty handed, because frankly I just couldnt be bothered to make a decision in this sweltering heat. It was one decision too many after having to select a pair of glasses from a hundred frames and choosing what I was going to have for supper from the shelves of chicken variations. Of course Im not really grumbling (and Id be certainly grumbling if the choice was taken away) but occasionally I like not to have to think. I was most impressed when I spoke to a New York bar owner last year on the 31 Days of Rieslingtrip to Germany who said for a month in his bar if customers wanted a white wine by the glass their only option was Riesling; the only decision they had to make was the country of origin and style. He said people loved being told what to do and as a result his like-by-like, by-the-glass sales shot up.\r\n\r\nI was recently in the Rhne Valley visiting Domaine Vintur which is owned by Englishman Graham Shore and overseen by his innovative Yorkshire born wine maker, James Wood. You know, its so nice, just to have a simple selection of good wines, I mused, staring at its concise, non fussy and clearly packaged range. Ive been on many a wine trip and when youre faced with a sea of bottles to taste from a single producer it can be very off-putting.  \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nSo, in the theme of things Ill keep it simple: The Domaine Vintur Cuve Le Gentleman 2011 (rrp 14.80), is aromatic and beautifully elegant. The Domaine Vintur White Tradition, Grenache Blanc, 2012 (rrp 10.56), really grew on me through the days visit and has obviously grown on others too, having won the Trophe Concours du Ventoux 2013 for the best white in the whole appellation. Plus the Domaine Vintur Ros 2012, Vin de Pays de la Mediterrane (9.71) was dry, clean and drinking perfectly on that beautiful French summers day.bibendum-wine.co.uk\r\n\r\n And with that in mind, ifI was eating out today Id go to Le Relais de Venise because there is no menu, which is not taxing to the brain at all. You just tell the waitress how you like your steak and then back it comes with salad and chips. Sometimes there''s a lot to be said about just keeping it simple. \r\n\r\n \r\n Share This \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n  ', 'The paradox of choice, by Carol Emmas', NULL, '/resources/food-drink/paradox-choice-carol-emmas', '2014-03-29 18:40:48', '2014-09-01 13:38:29', NULL, 0),
(311, 'How by-the-glass wines can boost restaurant profits, by Carol Emmas  As guests increasingly demand quality and value for money over quantity, particularly when it comes to wine, a by-the-glass offer can reap rewards. But how is it possible to give greater options without pouring away profits?\r\nOne way to appeal to consumers who want premium quality, but might not want to trade up to a bottle, is to use a wine preservation machine to increase the by-the-glass range. These have the potential to significantly reduce wastage, increase profits, and raise a venues drinks list reputation by offering wine flights and themed or comparative tastings.\r\nPreservation systems do not just prevent waste, they provide an opportunity to upsell to more expensive wines and increase profits.\r\nThis article appeared in Caterer and Hotelkeeper - to read the full article and see how operators are profiting from by-the-glass sales, click here \r\n Share This \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n  ', 'How by-the-glass wines can boost restaurant profits, by Carol Emmas', NULL, '/resources/profit/how-glass-wines-can-boost-restaurant-profits-carol-emmas', '2014-03-29 18:49:10', '2014-09-01 13:38:29', NULL, 0),
(312, 'How mobile apps can help your restaurant business, by Carol Emmas  Who would have anticipated even five years ago the mobile app would present us with such a wealth of business opportunity?With global revenue from app stores forecast to soar 62% this year, weve barely begun to explore what apps can and will be able to do for the restaurant and pub industry. Given that in the next couple of years they will increasingly become personalised and streamlined to individual business models, I take a look at whats out there currently, how they can drive business, and ask can there be any possible downsides?\r\n\r\nOne area that is generating a healthy interest in the hospitality industry is the restaurant payment app which is about to flood into the market and offers a wealth of advantages. This includes reducing the need to flag the waiter down for the bill, greater control for the customer and less hassle when it comes to issues such as bill splitting.\r\n\r\nChief executive officer of Flypay, Tom Weaver, says the most painful part of the customer experience is payment, which he claims takes an average of 10.2 minutes. In addition there is the time consuming issue of dividing the bill when consumers are in groups. Weaver is seeing its app take off in busier places such as in Wahaca in St Paul''s, London, where customers can pay by scanning a barcode on the table. Our consumer feedback shows that we are generating business through people with busy work commitments being more likely to eat out at lunch knowing they can pay quickly.Customers find getting this kind of control over their experience addictive and liberating - we''ve had people tell us they find going to restaurants without Flypay more frustrating in terms of payment than they did before. When you know what''s possible, you want it every time.\r\n\r\nTo see what other providers are offering and how it can change your business continue reading my cover feature in this month''s Eat Out here. \r\n Share This \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n  ', 'How mobile apps can help your restaurant business, by Carol Emmas', NULL, '/resources/marketing/how-mobile-apps-can-help-your-restaurant-business-carol-emmas', '2014-03-29 18:55:28', '2014-09-01 13:38:29', NULL, 0),
